\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{amsmath}
\usepackage{siunitx}

\begin{document}

\section*{Problem}

\begin{enumerate}
    \item[(a)] By considering a volume, \( V \), of ideal gas, containing \( N \) spherical molecules with radius \( r \), show that the mean free path of the molecules can be defined by the equation:
    \[
    \lambda = \frac{V}{4\pi \sqrt{2} r^2 N}
    \]

    \item[(b)] Hence, or otherwise, calculate the mean free path of air at \SI{100}{\degreeCelsius} and \SI{1.01e5}{\pascal}. Assume that the molecules of air are spheres of radius \( r = 2.0 \times 10^{-10} \, \text{m} \). \\
    (Boltzmann constant \( k = 1.38 \times 10^{-23} \, \text{J/K} \))
\end{enumerate}

\section*{Solution}

\subsection*{(a) Derivation of Mean Free Path}

The mean free path \( \lambda \) is the average distance a molecule travels before colliding with another molecule. For a gas with volume \( V \) and \( N \) molecules, the number density \( n \) is given by:
\[
n = \frac{N}{V}
\]

The effective cross-sectional area \( A \) for collision of two molecules, each with radius \( r \), is:
\[
A = \pi (2r)^2 = 4\pi r^2
\]

The mean free path \( \lambda \) is then given by:
\[
\lambda = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2} n A} = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2} \left(\frac{N}{V}\right) 4\pi r^2} = \frac{V}{4\pi \sqrt{2} r^2 N}
\]

\subsection*{(b) Calculation of Mean Free Path for Air}

Given:
\begin{align*}
r &= 2.0 \times 10^{-10} \, \text{m} \\
P &= 1.01 \times 10^5 \, \text{Pa} \\
T &= 100^\circ \text{C} = 373 \, \text{K} \\
k &= 1.38 \times 10^{-23} \, \text{J/K}
\end{align*}

Using the ideal gas law, \( PV = NkT \), we find the number density \( n \):
\[
n = \frac{P}{kT} = \frac{1.01 \times 10^5}{1.38 \times 10^{-23} \times 373}
\]

Substitute \( n \) and \( r \) into the expression for \( \lambda \):
\[
\lambda = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2} n 4\pi r^2}
\]

Calculate \( n \) and then \( \lambda \):
\[
n \approx \frac{1.01 \times 10^5}{1.38 \times 10^{-23} \times 373} \approx 2.45 \times 10^{25} \, \text{m}^{-3}
\]

\[
\lambda = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2} \times 2.45 \times 10^{25} \times 4\pi \times (2.0 \times 10^{-10})^2}
\]

\[
\lambda \approx 6.63 \times 10^{-8} \, \text{m}
\]

Thus, the mean free path of air at \SI{100}{\degreeCelsius} and \SI{1.01e5}{\pascal} is approximately \SI{66.3}{\nano\meter}.

\end{document}
```

