\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{amsmath}

\begin{document}

Consider $n$ slabs of the same thickness, with cross-sectional areas $A_1, A_2, \ldots, A_n$ and thermal conductivities $k_1, k_2, \ldots, k_n$. These slabs are placed in contact in parallel and maintained at temperatures $T_1$ and $T_2$. 

\begin{enumerate}
    \item[(a)] Calculate the rate of flow of heat through the composite slab.
    \item[(b)] Determine the equivalent thermal conductivity of the composite slab.
\end{enumerate}

\subsection*{Solution}

\subsubsection*{(a) Rate of Flow of Heat}

For slabs in parallel, the total rate of heat flow $Q$ through the composite slab is the sum of the heat flow through each slab. The rate of heat flow through the $i$-th slab is given by:

\[
Q_i = \frac{k_i A_i (T_1 - T_2)}{d}
\]

where $d$ is the thickness of each slab. Therefore, the total rate of heat flow is:

\[
Q = \sum_{i=1}^{n} Q_i = \sum_{i=1}^{n} \frac{k_i A_i (T_1 - T_2)}{d}
\]

\subsubsection*{(b) Equivalent Conductivity}

The equivalent thermal conductivity $k_{\text{eq}}$ for slabs in parallel is defined such that:

\[
Q = \frac{k_{\text{eq}} A_{\text{total}} (T_1 - T_2)}{d}
\]

where $A_{\text{total}} = \sum_{i=1}^{n} A_i$ is the total cross-sectional area. Equating the expressions for $Q$, we get:

\[
\frac{k_{\text{eq}} A_{\text{total}} (T_1 - T_2)}{d} = \sum_{i=1}^{n} \frac{k_i A_i (T_1 - T_2)}{d}
\]

Simplifying, the equivalent conductivity is:

\[
k_{\text{eq}} = \frac{\sum_{i=1}^{n} k_i A_i}{A_{\text{total}}}
\]

\end{document}
```

