\[
Q = m \cdot L = 0.05 \, \si{\kilogram} \times 3.3472 \times 10^5 \, \si{\joule\per\kilogram} = 16736 \, \si{\joule}
\]

The cross-sectional area \( A \) of the copper bar is:
\[
A = \pi \left(\frac{d}{2}\right)^2 = \pi \left(\frac{0.02}{2}\right)^2 = \pi \times 0.01^2 = \pi \times 10^{-4} \, \si{\meter\squared}
\]

Using Fourier's law of heat conduction, the rate of heat transfer \( \dot{Q} \) is given by:
\[
\dot{Q} = \frac{k \cdot A \cdot \Delta T}{L}
\]
where
\begin{align*}
k &= \SI{90}{\watt\per\meter\per\kelvin}, \\
\Delta T &= \SI{100}{\degreeCelsius} - \SI{0}{\degreeCelsius} = \SI{100}{\kelvin}, \\
L &= \SI{0.2}{\meter}.
\end{align*}

Substituting the values, we get:
\[
\dot{Q} = \frac{90 \times \pi \times 10^{-4} \times 100}{0.2} = 141.37 \, \si{\watt}
