\]

where \( m = \SI{3}{g} = \SI{0.003}{kg} \) and \( v = \SI{120}{m/s} \).

\[
K_i = \frac{1}{2} \times 0.003 \times (120)^2 = \SI{21.6}{J}
\]

Since \( 1 \, \text{cal} = \SI{4.184}{J} \), we convert the kinetic energy to calories:

\[
K_i = \frac{21.6}{4.184} \approx \SI{5.16}{cal}
\]

The rise in temperature \( \Delta T \) of the bullet is given by:

\[
Q = m c \Delta T
\]

where \( Q = \SI{5.16}{cal} \), \( m = \SI{3}{g} \), and \( c = \SI{0.031}{cal/g^\circ C} \).

\[
\Delta T = \frac{Q}{m c} = \frac{5.16}{3 \times 0.031} \approx \SI{55.48}{^\circ C}
\]

\subsection*{(b) Block is free to move}

When the block is free to move, the bullet and block move together after the collision. Using conservation of momentum:

\[
m_{\text{bullet}} v_{\text{bullet}} = (m_{\text{bullet}} + m_{\text{block}}) v_f
\]

where \( m_{\text{block}} = \SI{50}{g} = \SI{0.05}{kg} \).

\[
0.003 \times 120 = (0.003 + 0.05) v_f
\]

\[
v_f = \frac{0.003 \times 120}{0.053} \approx \SI{6.79}{m/s}
\]

The final kinetic energy \( K_f \) of the system is:

\[
K_f = \frac{1}{2} (0.003 + 0.05) (6.79)^2 \approx \SI{1.56}{J}
\]

The kinetic energy converted to thermal energy is:

\[
\Delta K = K_i - K_f = 21.6 - 1.56 = \SI{20.04}{J}
\]

Convert this energy to calories:

\[
\Delta K = \frac{20.04}{4.184} \approx \SI{4.79}{cal}
\]

