\section*{Physics Problems and Solutions}

\subsection*{(a) Carnot Cycle Efficiency}

The efficiency of a Carnot cycle can be expressed in two ways:

\begin{enumerate}
    \item \textbf{In terms of heat flows:}
    \[
    \eta = 1 - \frac{Q_C}{Q_H}
    \]
    where \( Q_H \) is the heat absorbed from the hot reservoir and \( Q_C \) is the heat expelled to the cold reservoir.

    \item \textbf{In terms of temperatures:}
    \[
    \eta = 1 - \frac{T_C}{T_H}
    \]
    where \( T_H \) is the absolute temperature of the hot reservoir and \( T_C \) is the absolute temperature of the cold reservoir.
\end{enumerate}

\subsection*{(b) Otto Engine and Efficiency}

The Otto cycle is the idealized cycle for a spark-ignition internal combustion engine. The efficiency of the air standard Otto cycle can be expressed as a function of temperature and volume.

\begin{figure}[h]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=0.6\textwidth]{otto_cycle_pv_diagram.png}
    \caption{P-V Diagram of the Otto Cycle}
\end{figure}

\textbf{Steps of the Otto Cycle:}

\begin{enumerate}
    \item \textbf{Adiabatic Compression (1 to 2):} The gas is compressed adiabatically from volume \( V_1 \) to volume \( V_2 \), resulting in an increase in temperature from \( T_1 \) to \( T_2 \).

    \item \textbf{Constant Volume Heat Addition (2 to 3):} Heat is added at constant volume, increasing the temperature from \( T_2 \) to \( T_3 \).

    \item \textbf{Adiabatic Expansion (3 to 4):} The gas expands adiabatically from volume \( V_2 \) to volume \( V_1 \), and the temperature decreases from \( T_3 \) to \( T_4 \).

    \item \textbf{Constant Volume Heat Rejection (4 to 1):} Heat is rejected at constant volume, decreasing the temperature from \( T_4 \) to \( T_1 \).
\end{enumerate}

\textbf{Efficiency of the Otto Cycle:}
\[
\eta = 1 - \left( \frac{V_1}{V_2} \right)^{\gamma - 1} = 1 - \frac{T_4 - T_1}{T_3 - T_2}
\]
where \( \gamma \) is the heat capacity ratio \( \frac{C_p}{C_v} \).

\subsection*{(c) Comparison of Carnot and Stirling Cycles}

The Carnot and Stirling cycles can be compared using P-V diagrams. The Carnot cycle consists of two isothermal and two adiabatic processes, while the Stirling cycle consists of two isothermal and two isochoric (constant volume) processes.

\begin{figure}[h]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=0.6\textwidth]{carnot_stirling_pv_diagram.png}
    \caption{Comparison of Carnot and Stirling Cycles on a P-V Diagram}
\end{figure}

The Carnot cycle is the most efficient cycle for a given temperature difference, but the Stirling cycle is more practical for real-world applications due to its simpler implementation.

