A mole of gaseous molecules in a bubble obeys the ideal gas law. What is the volume of the bubble at a 100 m depth of water if the temperature is 293 K, the atmospheric pressure is 101 kPa, density of water is 1000 kg/m\textsuperscript{3}, and the ideal gas constant is 8.314 J/mol/K? [University of Manchester 2008]

\section*{Solution}

To find the volume of the bubble, we use the ideal gas law:

\begin{equation}
    PV = nRT
\end{equation}

where:
\begin{align*}
    P & = \text{pressure at depth} \\
    V & = \text{volume of the bubble} \\
    n & = \text{number of moles} = 1 \text{ mol} \\
    R & = \text{ideal gas constant} = 8.314 \text{ J/mol/K} \\
    T & = \text{temperature} = 293 \text{ K}
\end{align*}

First, calculate the pressure at a depth of 100 m in water. The pressure at this depth is the sum of atmospheric pressure and the pressure due to the water column:

\begin{equation}
    P_{\text{depth}} = P_{\text{atm}} + \rho g h
\end{equation}

where:
\begin{align*}
    P_{\text{atm}} & = 101 \text{ kPa} = 101,000 \text{ Pa} \\
    \rho & = \text{density of water} = 1000 \text{ kg/m}^3 \\
    g & = \text{acceleration due to gravity} \approx 9.81 \text{ m/s}^2 \\
    h & = \text{depth} = 100 \text{ m}
\end{align*}

Substituting the values, we get:

\begin{equation}
    P_{\text{depth}} = 101,000 + (1000 \times 9.81 \times 100)
\end{equation}

\begin{equation}
    P_{\text{depth}} = 101,000 + 981,000 = 1,082,000 \text{ Pa}
\end{equation}

Now, substitute $P_{\text{depth}}$, $n$, $R$, and $T$ into the ideal gas law to find $V$:

\begin{equation}
    V = \frac{nRT}{P_{\text{depth}}}
\end{equation}

\begin{equation}
    V = \frac{1 \times 8.314 \times 293}{1,082,000}
\end{equation}

\begin{equation}
    V \approx \frac{2434.502}{1,082,000} \approx 0.00225 \text{ m}^3
\end{equation}

Thus, the volume of the bubble at a 100 m depth is approximately 0.00225 m\textsuperscript{3}.

